cip_code.name: Computer and Information Sciences, General.
cip_code.definition: A general program that focuses on computing, computer science, and information science and systems. Such programs are undifferentiated as to title and content and are not to be confused with specific programs in computer science, information science, or related support services.

master_cip_code.name: COMPUTER AND INFORMATION SCIENCES AND SUPPORT SERVICES.
master_cip_code.definition: Instructional programs that focus on the computer and information sciences and prepare individuals for various occupations in information technology and computer operations fields.

course.name: College Algebra
course.description: This course develops the algebraic skills necessary for further studies in matematics. topics include the algebra of functions; graphing techniques; quantitative and qualitative analysis of polynomial, rational, exponential and logarithmic functions, including limits at infinity and infinite limits; and appropriate applications. Prerequisite: Successful completion of an Intermediate Algebra course with a grade of C or higher, an ACT math sub-score of 22 (or higher), a SAT math sub-score of 510 (or higher), a KYOTE College Algebra Placement score of 14 (or higher, or a COMPASS score of 50 (or higher). CREDIT: THREE SEMESTER HOURS

prereq.description: MAT 097 with grade of C or higher or appropriate scores on ACT, SAT, or placement test.

course.name: Intro. to University Learning
course.description: This course is an introduction to the college experience and the opportunity to explore the skills and expectations necessary at the college level. In alignment with the student learning outcomes, students will explore the psychology of success, adapt to effective learning behaviors, and understand the science of learning. This course provides a learning opportunity for the student which includes communication skills, critical reasoning, problem solving, study skills, time management, and goal setting. The content of the course is designed to help students in becoming more independent learners in order that they can make the most of their educational opportunities. Additionally, the course will expose students to the history, numerous resources, and services available at Kentucky State University. Students will learn how to enhance their current study skills toward developing a foundation for lifelong learning and career development.
